    <div xml:id="PN392">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>matiyēr veṇkuṭai yatiyar kōmāṉ</l>
<l>koṭumpū ṇeḻiṉi neṭuṅkaṭai niṉṟiyāṉ</l>
<l>pacalai nilaviṉ paṉipaṭu viṭiyaṟ</l>
<l>porukaḷiṟ ṟaṭivaḻi yaṉṉa veṉkai</l>
<l>yorukaṇ mākkiṇai yoṟṟupu koṭāa</l>
<l>vurukeḻu maṉṉa rāreyil kaṭantu</l>
<l>niṇampaṭu kurutip perumpāṭ ṭīrat</l>
<l>taṇaṅkuṭai marapi ṉiruṅkaḷan tōṟum</l>
<l>veḷvāyk kaḻutaip pulliṉam pūṭṭi</l>
<l>veḷḷai varakuṅ koḷḷum vittum</l>
<l>vaika luḻava vāḻiya periteṉac</l>
<l>ceṉṟiyā ṉiṉṟaṉe ṉāka vaṉṟē</l>
<l>yūruṇ kēṇip pakaṭṭilaip pāci</l>
<l>vērpurai citāar nīkki nērkarai</l>
<l>nuṇṇūṟ kaliṅka muṭīi yuṇṇeṉat</l>
<l>tēṭkaṭup paṉṉa nāṭpaṭu tēṟal</l>
<l>kōṇmī ṉaṉṉa polaṅkalat taḷaii</l>
<l>yūṇmuṟai yītta laṉṟiyuṅ kōṇmuṟai</l>
<l>viruntiṟai nalki yōṉē yantarat</l>
<l>tarumpeṟa lamiḻta maṉṉa</l>
<l>karumpivaṭ ṭantōṉ perumpiṟaṅ kaṭaiyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>As I standing at the tall gate of Eḻiṉi with curved ornaments, (2)</l>
<l>the king of the Atiyar with a moon-like white parasol, (1)</l>
<l>a dawn when dew fell in the pale moonlight (3)</l>
<l>pressing the one-eyed big Kiṇai drum (5a-c)</l>
<l>in my hand like the trace of the feet of a fighting elephant bull, (4)</l>
<l>[and] saying (11d)</l>
<l>“you who overcome the fortresses difficult [to conquer] of feardul kings who do not give [tribute], (6)</l>
<l>yoke grass[-eating] groups of white donkeys (9)</l>
<l>according to frightful custom on every great battle field (8)</l>
<l>with the wetness of great events of blood falling with fat, (7)</l>
<l>[and] sow white wild millet and babul, (10)</l>
<l>ploughman, may you live long for [many] days”, (11)</l>
<l>having gone I stood [there], on that very day (12)</l>
<l>he removed the rags resembling the roots (14a-c)</l>
<l>of lichen with huge leaves in the drinking well of a village, (13)</l>
<l>put [on me] a Kaliṅkam cloth with thin threads [and] a fine border, (14d-15c)</l>
<l>	saying “eat!”, </l>
<l>mixed in a golden vessel like the stars of an asterism (17)</l>
<l>toddy made [that] day that [stung] like the throbbing of a scorpion’s [attack] (16)</l>
<l>and apart from giving courses of food (18a-c)</l>
<l>he granted a seat at [his] feast in the order of taking, (19a-c)</l>
<l>he gave here sugarcane (21ab)</l>
<l>that was like difficult to obtain ambrosia from heaven, (19d-29)</l>
<l>	the great descendant. (21d)</l>
</lg>
